        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000028": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000028",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-65fb807d23063af6-7a2b93 twpub-65fb807d23063af6-de533d twpub-65fb807d23063af6-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"c2\"><br>\n<br>\n<br>\n<br></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000029": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000029",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-65fb807d23063af6-7a2b93 twpub-65fb807d23063af6-de533d twpub-65fb807d23063af6-6b4cd0\"><h2>THE TRAGICAL HISTORY OF DOCTOR FAUSTUS</h2></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000030": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000030",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-65fb807d23063af6-7a2b93 twpub-65fb807d23063af6-de533d twpub-65fb807d23063af6-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"pgmonospaced\">FROM THE QUARTO OF 1604.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter CHORUS.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CHORUS. Not marching now in fields of Thrasymene,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Where Mars did mate<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000035\">1</$link> the Carthaginians;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Nor sporting in the dalliance of love,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  In courts of kings where state is overturn'd;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Nor in the pomp of proud audacious deeds,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Intends our Muse to vaunt<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000037\">2</$link> her<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000039\">3</$link> heavenly verse:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Only this, gentlemen,âwe must perform\n<br>Â Â Â Â  The form of Faustus' fortunes, good or bad:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  To patient judgments we appeal our plaud,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And speak for Faustus in his infancy.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Now is he born, his parents base of stock,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  In Germany, within a town call'd Rhodes:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Of riper years, to Wertenberg he went,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Whereas<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000041\">4</$link> his kinsmen chiefly brought him up.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  So soon he profits in divinity,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  The fruitful plot of scholarism grac'd,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  That shortly he was grac'd with doctor's name,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Excelling all whose sweet delight disputes\n<br>Â Â Â Â  In heavenly matters of theology;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Till swoln with cunning,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000043\">5</$link> of a self-conceit,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  His waxen wings did mount above his reach,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And, melting, heavens conspir'd his overthrow;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  For, falling to a devilish exercise,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And glutted now<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000045\">6</$link> with learning's golden gifts,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  He surfeits upon cursed necromancy;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Nothing so sweet as magic is to him,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Which he prefers before his chiefest bliss:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And this the man that in his study sits.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exit.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS discovered in his study.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000047\">7</$link>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Settle thy studies, Faustus, and begin\n<br>Â Â Â Â  To sound the depth of that thou wilt profess:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Having commenc'd, be a divine in shew,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Yet level at the end of every art,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And live and die in Aristotle's works.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Sweet Analytics, 'tis thou<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000049\">8</$link> hast ravish'd me!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Bene disserere est finis logices.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Is, to dispute well, logic's chiefest end?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Affords this art no greater miracle?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Then read no more; thou hast attain'd that<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000051\">9</$link> end:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  A greater subject fitteth Faustus' wit:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Bid Economy<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000053\">10</$link> farewell, and<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000055\">11</$link> Galen come,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Seeing, Ubi desinit philosophus, ibi incipit medicus:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Be a physician, Faustus; heap up gold,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And be eterniz'd for some wondrous cure:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Summum bonum medicinae sanitas,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  The end of physic is our body's health.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Why, Faustus, hast thou not attain'd that end?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Is not thy common talk found aphorisms?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Are not thy bills hung up as monuments,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Whereby whole cities have escap'd the plague,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And thousand desperate maladies been eas'd?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Yet art thou still but Faustus, and a man.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Couldst<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000057\">12</$link> thou make men<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000059\">13</$link> to live eternally,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Or, being dead, raise them to life again,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Then this profession were to be esteem'd.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Physic, farewell!Â  Where is Justinian?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Reads.]\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Si una eademque res legatur<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000061\">14</$link> duobus, alter rem,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  alter valorem rei, &amp;c.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  A pretty case of paltry legacies!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Reads.]\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Exhoereditare filium non potest pater, nisi, &amp;c.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000063\">15</$link>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Such is the subject of the institute,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And universal body of the law:<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000065\">16</$link>Â Â Â Â  This<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000067\">17</$link> study fits a mercenary drudge,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Who aims at nothing but external trash;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Too servile<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000069\">18</$link> and illiberal for me.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  When all is done, divinity is best:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Jerome's Bible, Faustus; view it well.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Reads.]\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Stipendium peccati mors est.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Ha!\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Stipendium, &amp;c.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  The reward of sin is death:Â  that's hard.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Reads.]\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Si peccasse negamus, fallimur, et nulla est in nobis veritas;\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  If we say that we have no sin, we deceive ourselves, and\n<br>Â Â Â Â  there's no truth in us.Â  Why, then, belike we must sin, and so\n<br>Â Â Â Â  consequently die:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Ay, we must die an everlasting death.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  What doctrine call you this, Che sera, sera,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000071\">19</$link>Â Â Â Â  What will be, shall be?Â  Divinity, adieu!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  These metaphysics of magicians,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And necromantic books are heavenly;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Lines, circles, scenes,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000073\">20</$link> letters, and characters;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Ay, these are those that Faustus most desires.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  O, what a world of profit and delight,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Of power, of honour, of omnipotence,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Is promis'd to the studious artizan!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  All things that move between the quiet poles\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Shall be at my command:Â  emperors and kings\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Are but obeyed in their several provinces,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Nor can they raise the wind, or rend the clouds;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  But his dominion that exceeds in this,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Stretcheth as far as doth the mind of man;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  A sound magician is a mighty god:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Here, Faustus, tire<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000075\">21</$link> thy brains to gain a deity.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter WAGNER.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000077\">22</$link>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Wagner, commend me to my dearest friends,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  The German Valdes and Cornelius;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Request them earnestly to visit me.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. I will, sir.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exit.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Their conference will be a greater help to me\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Than all my labours, plod I ne'er so fast.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter GOOD ANGEL and EVIL ANGEL.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  GOOD ANGEL. O, Faustus, lay that damned book aside,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And gaze not on it, lest it tempt thy soul,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And heap God's heavy wrath upon thy head!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Read, read the Scriptures:âthat is blasphemy.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  EVIL ANGEL. Go forward, Faustus, in that famous art\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Wherein all Nature's treasure<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000079\">23</$link> is contain'd:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Be thou on earth as Jove<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000081\">24</$link> is in the sky,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Lord and commander of these elements.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000083\">25</$link>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exeunt Angels.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. How am I glutted with conceit of this!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Shall I make spirits fetch me what I please,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Resolve<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000085\">26</$link> me of all ambiguities,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Perform what desperate enterprise I will?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I'll have them fly to India for gold,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Ransack the ocean for orient pearl,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And search all corners of the new-found world\n<br>Â Â Â Â  For pleasant fruits and princely delicates;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I'll have them read me strange philosophy,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And tell the secrets of all foreign kings;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I'll have them wall all Germany with brass,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And make swift Rhine circle fair Wertenberg;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I'll have them fill the public schools with silk,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000087\">27</$link>Â Â Â Â  Wherewith the students shall be bravely clad;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I'll levy soldiers with the coin they bring,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And chase the Prince of Parma from our land,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And reign sole king of all the<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000089\">28</$link> provinces;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Yea, stranger engines for the brunt of war,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Than was the fiery keel at Antwerp's bridge,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000091\">29</$link>Â Â Â Â  I'll make my servile spirits to invent.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter VALDES and CORNELIUS.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Come, German Valdes, and Cornelius,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And make me blest with your sage conference.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Valdes, sweet Valdes, and Cornelius,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Know that your words have won me at the last\n<br>Â Â Â Â  To practice magic and concealed arts:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Yet not your words only,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000093\">30</$link> but mine own fantasy,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  That will receive no object; for my head\n<br>Â Â Â Â  But ruminates on necromantic skill.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Philosophy is odious and obscure;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Both law and physic are for petty wits;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Divinity is basest of the three,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Unpleasant, harsh, contemptible, and vile:<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000095\">31</$link>Â Â Â Â  'Tis magic, magic, that hath ravish'd me.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Then, gentle friends, aid me in this attempt;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And I, that have with concise syllogisms<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000098\">32</$link>Â Â Â Â  Gravell'd the pastors of the German church,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And made the flowering pride of Wertenberg\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Swarm to my problems, as the infernal spirits\n<br>Â Â Â Â  On sweet Musaeus when he came to hell,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Will be as cunning<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000100\">33</$link> as Agrippa<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000102\">34</$link> was,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Whose shadow<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000104\">35</$link> made all Europe honour him.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  VALDES. Faustus, these books, thy wit, and our experience,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Shall make all nations to canonize us.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  As Indian Moors obey their Spanish lords,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  So shall the spirits<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000106\">36</$link> of every element\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Be always serviceable to us three;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Like lions shall they guard us when we please;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Like Almain rutters<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000108\">37</$link> with their horsemen's staves,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Or Lapland giants, trotting by our sides;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Sometimes like women, or unwedded maids,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Shadowing more beauty in their airy brows\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Than have the<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000111\">38</$link> white breasts of the queen of love:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  From<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000113\">39</$link> Venice shall they drag huge argosies,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And from America the golden fleece\n<br>Â Â Â Â  That yearly stuffs old Philip's treasury;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  If learned Faustus will be resolute.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Valdes, as resolute am I in this\n<br>Â Â Â Â  As thou to live:Â  therefore object it not.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CORNELIUS. The miracles that magic will perform\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Will make thee vow to study nothing else.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  He that is grounded in astrology,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Enrich'd with tongues, well seen in<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000115\">40</$link> minerals,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Hath all the principles magic doth require:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Then doubt not, Faustus, but to be renowm'd,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000117\">41</$link>Â Â Â Â  And more frequented for this mystery\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Than heretofore the Delphian oracle.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  The spirits tell me they can dry the sea,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And fetch the treasure of all foreign wrecks,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Ay, all the wealth that our forefathers hid\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Within the massy entrails of the earth:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Then tell me, Faustus, what shall we three want?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Nothing, Cornelius.Â  O, this cheers my soul!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Come, shew me some demonstrations magical,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  That I may conjure in some lusty grove,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And have these joys in full possession.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  VALDES. Then haste thee to some solitary grove,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And bear wise Bacon's and Albertus'<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000120\">42</$link> works,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  The Hebrew Psalter, and New Testament;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And whatsoever else is requisite\n<br>Â Â Â Â  We will inform thee ere our conference cease.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CORNELIUS. Valdes, first let him know the words of art;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And then, all other ceremonies learn'd,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Faustus may try his cunning<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000122\">43</$link> by himself.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  VALDES. First I'll instruct thee in the rudiments,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And then wilt thou be perfecter than I.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Then come and dine with me, and, after meat,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  We'll canvass every quiddity thereof;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  For, ere I sleep, I'll try what I can do:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  This night I'll conjure, though I die therefore.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exeunt.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter two SCHOLARS.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000124\">44</$link>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FIRST SCHOLAR. I wonder what's become of Faustus, that was wont\n<br>Â Â Â Â  to make our schools ring with sic probo.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  SECOND SCHOLAR. That shall we know, for see, here comes his boy.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter WAGNER.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FIRST SCHOLAR. How now, sirrah! where's thy master?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. God in heaven knows.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  SECOND SCHOLAR. Why, dost not thou know?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. Yes, I know; but that follows not.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FIRST SCHOLAR. Go to, sirrah! leave your jesting, and tell us\n<br>Â Â Â Â  where he is.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. That follows not necessary by force of argument, that you,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  being licentiates, should stand upon:<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000126\">45</$link>Â  therefore acknowledge\n<br>Â Â Â Â  your error, and be attentive.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  SECOND SCHOLAR. Why, didst thou not say thou knewest?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. Have you any witness on't?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FIRST SCHOLAR. Yes, sirrah, I heard you.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. Ask my fellow if I be a thief.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  SECOND SCHOLAR. Well, you will not tell us?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. Yes, sir, I will tell you:Â  yet, if you were not dunces,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  you would never ask me such a question; for is not he corpus\n<br>Â Â Â Â  naturale? and is not that mobile? then wherefore should you\n<br>Â Â Â Â  ask me such a question?Â  But that I am by nature phlegmatic,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  slow to wrath, and prone to lechery (to love, I would say),\n<br>Â Â Â Â  it were not for you to come within forty foot of the place\n<br>Â Â Â Â  of execution, although I do not doubt to see you both hanged\n<br>Â Â Â Â  the next sessions.Â  Thus having triumphed over you, I will set\n<br>Â Â Â Â  my countenance like a precisian, and begin to speak thus:â\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Truly, my dear brethren, my master is within at dinner,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  with Valdes and Cornelius, as this wine, if it could speak,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  would<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000128\">46</$link> inform your worships:Â  and so, the Lord bless you,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  preserve you, and keep you, my dear brethren, my dear brethren!<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000130\">47</$link>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exit.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FIRST SCHOLAR. Nay, then, I fear he is fallen into that damned art\n<br>Â Â Â Â  for which they two are infamous through the world.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  SECOND SCHOLAR. Were he a stranger, and not allied to me, yet should\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I grieve for him. But, come, let us go and inform the Rector,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  and see if he by his grave counsel can reclaim him.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FIRST SCHOLAR. O, but I fear me nothing can reclaim him!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  SECOND SCHOLAR. Yet let us try what we can do.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exeunt.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter FAUSTUS to conjure.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000132\">48</$link>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Now that the gloomy shadow of the earth,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Longing to view Orion's drizzling look,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Leaps from th' antartic world unto the sky,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And dims the welkin with her pitchy breath,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Faustus, begin thine incantations,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And try if devils will obey thy hest,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Seeing thou hast pray'd and sacrific'd to them.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Within this circle is Jehovah's name,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Forward and backward anagrammatiz'd,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000134\">49</$link>Â Â Â Â  Th' abbreviated<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000136\">50</$link> names of holy saints,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Figures of every adjunct to the heavens,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And characters of signs and erring<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000138\">51</$link> stars,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  By which the spirits are enforc'd to rise:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Then fear not, Faustus, but be resolute,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And try the uttermost magic can perform.â\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Sint mihi dei Acherontis propitii!Â  Valeat numen triplex Jehovoe!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Ignei, aerii, aquatani spiritus, salvete!Â  Orientis princeps\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Belzebub, inferni ardentis monarcha, et Demogorgon, propitiamus\n<br>Â Â Â Â  vos, ut appareat et surgat Mephistophilis, quod tumeraris:<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000140\">52</$link>Â Â Â Â  per Jehovam, Gehennam, et consecratam aquam quam nunc spargo,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  signumque crucis quod nunc facio, et per vota nostra, ipse nunc\n<br>Â Â Â Â  surgat nobis dicatus<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000142\">53</$link> Mephistophilis!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter MEPHISTOPHILIS.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I charge thee to return, and change thy shape;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Thou art too ugly to attend on me:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Go, and return an old Franciscan friar;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  That holy shape becomes a devil best.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exit MEPHISTOPHILIS.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I see there's virtue in my heavenly words:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Who would not be proficient in this art?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  How pliant is this Mephistophilis,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Full of obedience and humility!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Such is the force of magic and my spells:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  No, Faustus, thou art conjuror laureat,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  That canst command great Mephistophilis:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Quin regis Mephistophilis fratris imagine.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Re-enter MEPHISTOPHILIS like a Franciscan friar.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000144\">54</$link>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Now, Faustus, what wouldst thou have me do?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. I charge thee wait upon me whilst I live,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  To do whatever Faustus shall command,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Be it to make the moon drop from her sphere,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Or the ocean to overwhelm the world.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. I am a servant to great Lucifer,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And may not follow thee without his leave:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  No more than he commands must we perform.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Did not he charge thee to appear to me?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. No, I came hither<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000146\">55</$link> of mine own accord.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Did not my conjuring speeches raise thee? speak.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. That was the cause, but yet per accidens;<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000148\">56</$link>Â Â Â Â  For, when we hear one rack the name of God,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Abjure the Scriptures and his Saviour Christ,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  We fly, in hope to get his glorious soul;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Nor will we come, unless he use such means\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Whereby he is in danger to be damn'd.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Therefore the shortest cut for conjuring\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Is stoutly to abjure the Trinity,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And pray devoutly to the prince of hell.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. So Faustus hath\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Already done; and holds this principle,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  There is no chief but only Belzebub;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  To whom Faustus doth dedicate himself.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  This word &quot;damnation&quot; terrifies not him,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  For he confounds hell in Elysium:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  His ghost be with the old philosophers!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  But, leaving these vain trifles of men's souls,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Tell me what is that Lucifer thy lord?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Arch-regent and commander of all spirits.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Was not that Lucifer an angel once?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Yes, Faustus, and most dearly lov'd of God.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. How comes it, then, that he is prince of devils?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. O, by aspiring pride and insolence;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  For which God threw him from the face of heaven.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. And what are you that live with Lucifer?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Unhappy spirits that fell with Lucifer,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Conspir'd against our God with Lucifer,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And are for ever damn'd with Lucifer.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Where are you damn'd?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. In hell.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. How comes it, then, that thou art out of hell?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Why, this is hell, nor am I out of it:<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000150\">57</$link>Â Â Â Â  Think'st thou that I, who saw the face of God,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And tasted the eternal joys of heaven,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Am not tormented with ten thousand hells,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  In being depriv'd of everlasting bliss?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  O, Faustus, leave these frivolous demands,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Which strike a terror to my fainting soul!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. What, is great Mephistophilis so passionate\n<br>Â Â Â Â  For being deprived of the joys of heaven?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Learn thou of Faustus manly fortitude,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And scorn those joys thou never shalt possess.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Go bear these<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000152\">58</$link> tidings to great Lucifer:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Seeing Faustus hath incurr'd eternal death\n<br>Â Â Â Â  By desperate thoughts against Jove's<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000154\">59</$link> deity,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Say, he surrenders up to him his soul,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  So he will spare him four and twenty<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000156\">60</$link> years,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Letting him live in all voluptuousness;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Having thee ever to attend on me,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  To give me whatsoever I shall ask,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  To tell me whatsoever I demand,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  To slay mine enemies, and aid my friends,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And always be obedient to my will.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Go and return to mighty Lucifer,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And meet me in my study at midnight,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And then resolve<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000158\">61</$link> me of thy master's mind.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. I will, Faustus.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exit.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Had I as many souls as there be stars,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I'd give them all for Mephistophilis.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  By him I'll be great emperor of the world,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And make a bridge thorough<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000160\">62</$link> the moving air,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  To pass the ocean with a band of men;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I'll join the hills that bind the Afric shore,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And make that country<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000162\">63</$link> continent to Spain,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And both contributory to my crown:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  The Emperor shall not live but by my leave,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Nor any potentate of Germany.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Now that I have obtain'd what I desir'd,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000164\">64</$link>Â Â Â Â  I'll live in speculation of this art,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Till Mephistophilis return again.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exit.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter WAGNER<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000166\">65</$link> and CLOWN.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. Sirrah boy, come hither.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CLOWN. How, boy! swowns, boy!Â  I hope you have seen many boys\n<br>Â Â Â Â  with such pickadevaunts<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000168\">66</$link> as I have:Â  boy, quotha!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. Tell me, sirrah, hast thou any comings in?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CLOWN. Ay, and goings out too; you may see else.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. Alas, poor slave! see how poverty jesteth in his nakedness!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  the villain is bare and out of service, and so hungry, that I know\n<br>Â Â Â Â  he would give his soul to the devil for a shoulder of mutton,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  though it were blood-raw.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CLOWN. How! my soul to the devil for a shoulder of mutton, though\n<br>Â Â Â Â  'twere blood-raw! not so, good friend:Â  by'r lady,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000170\">67</$link> I had need\n<br>Â Â Â Â  have it well roasted, and good sauce to it, if I pay so dear.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. Well, wilt thou serve me, and I'll make thee go like\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Qui mihi discipulus?<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000172\">68</$link>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CLOWN. How, in verse?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. No, sirrah; in beaten silk and staves-acre.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000175\">69</$link>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CLOWN. How, how, knaves-acre! ay, I thought that was all the land\n<br>Â Â Â Â  his father left him.Â  Do you hear?Â  I would be sorry to rob you of\n<br>Â Â Â Â  your living.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. Sirrah, I say in staves-acre.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CLOWN. Oho, oho, staves-acre! why, then, belike, if I were your\n<br>Â Â Â Â  man, I should be full of vermin.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000177\">70</$link>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. So thou shalt, whether thou beest with me or no.Â  But,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  sirrah, leave your jesting, and bind yourself presently unto me\n<br>Â Â Â Â  for seven years, or I'll turn all the lice about thee into\n<br>Â Â Â Â  familiars,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000179\">71</$link> and they shall tear thee in pieces.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CLOWN. Do you hear, sir? you may save that labour; they are too\n<br>Â Â Â Â  familiar with me already:Â  swowns, they are as bold with my flesh\n<br>Â Â Â Â  as if they had paid for their<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000181\">72</$link> meat and drink.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. Well, do you hear, sirrah? hold, take these guilders.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Gives money.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CLOWN. Gridirons! what be they?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. Why, French crowns.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CLOWN. Mass, but for the name of French crowns, a man were as good\n<br>Â Â Â Â  have as many English counters.Â  And what should I do with these?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. Why, now, sirrah, thou art at an hour's warning, whensoever\n<br>Â Â Â Â  or wheresoever the devil shall fetch thee.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CLOWN. No, no; here, take your gridirons again.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. Truly, I'll none of them.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CLOWN. Truly, but you shall.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. Bear witness I gave them him.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CLOWN. Bear witness I give them you again.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. Well, I will cause two devils presently to fetch thee\n<br>Â Â Â Â  away.âBaliol and Belcher!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CLOWN. Let your Baliol and your Belcher come here, and I'll\n<br>Â Â Â Â  knock them, they were never so knocked since they were devils:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  say I should kill one of them, what would folks say?Â  &quot;Do ye see\n<br>Â Â Â Â  yonder tall fellow in the round slop?<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000183\">73</$link> he has killed the devil.&quot;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  So I should be called Kill-devil all the parish over.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter two DEVILS; and the CLOWN runs up and down crying.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. Baliol and Belcher,âspirits, away!\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exeunt DEVILS.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CLOWN. What, are they gone? a vengeance on them! they have vile<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000185\">74</$link>Â Â Â Â  long nails.Â  There was a he-devil and a she-devil:Â  I'll tell you\n<br>Â Â Â Â  how you shall know them; all he-devils has horns, and all\n<br>Â Â Â Â  she-devils has clifts and cloven feet.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. Well, sirrah, follow me.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CLOWN. But, do you hear? if I should serve you, would you teach\n<br>Â Â Â Â  me to raise up Banios and Belcheos?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. I will teach thee to turn thyself to any thing, to a dog,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  or a cat, or a mouse, or a rat, or any thing.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CLOWN. How! a Christian fellow to a dog, or a cat, a mouse,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  or a rat! no, no, sir; if you turn me into any thing, let it be\n<br>Â Â Â Â  in the likeness of a little pretty frisking flea, that I may be\n<br>Â Â Â Â  here and there and every where:Â  O, I'll tickle the pretty wenches'\n<br>Â Â Â Â  plackets!Â  I'll be amongst them, i'faith.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. Well, sirrah, come.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CLOWN. But, do you hear, Wagner?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. How!âBaliol and Belcher!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CLOWN. O Lord!Â  I pray, sir, let Banio and Belcher go sleep.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. Villain, call me Master Wagner, and let thy left eye be\n<br>Â Â Â Â  diametarily fixed upon my right heel, with quasi vestigiis\n<br>Â Â Â Â  nostris<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000188\">75</$link> insistere.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exit.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CLOWN. God forgive me, he speaks Dutch fustian.Â  Well, I'll follow\n<br>Â Â Â Â  him; I'll serve him, that's flat.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exit.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS discovered in his study.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Now, Faustus, must\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Thou needs be damn'd, and canst thou not be sav'd:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  What boots it, then, to think of God or heaven?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Away with such vain fancies, and despair;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Despair in God, and trust in Belzebub:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Now go not backward; no, Faustus, be resolute:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Why waver'st thou?Â  O, something soundeth in mine ears,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  &quot;Abjure this magic, turn to God again!&quot;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Ay, and Faustus will turn to God again.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  To God? he loves thee not;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  The god thou serv'st is thine own appetite,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Wherein is fix'd the love of Belzebub:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  To him I'll build an altar and a church,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And offer lukewarm blood of new-born babes.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter GOOD ANGEL and EVIL ANGEL.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  GOOD ANGEL. Sweet Faustus, leave that execrable art.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Contrition, prayer, repentanceâwhat of them?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  GOOD ANGEL. O, they are means to bring thee unto heaven!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  EVIL ANGEL. Rather illusions, fruits of lunacy,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  That make men foolish that do trust them most.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  GOOD ANGEL. Sweet Faustus, think of heaven and heavenly things.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  EVIL ANGEL. No, Faustus; think of honour and of<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000190\">76</$link> wealth.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exeunt ANGELS.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Of wealth!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Why, the signiory of Embden shall be mine.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  When Mephistophilis shall stand by me,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  What god can hurt thee, Faustus? thou art safe\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Cast no more doubts.âCome, Mephistophilis,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And bring glad tidings from great Lucifer;â\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Is't not midnight?âcome, Mephistophilis,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Veni, veni, Mephistophile!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter MEPHISTOPHILIS.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Now tell me<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000192\">77</$link> what says Lucifer, thy lord?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. That I shall wait on Faustus whilst he lives,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000194\">78</$link>Â Â Â Â  So he will buy my service with his soul.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Already Faustus hath hazarded that for thee.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. But, Faustus, thou must bequeath it solemnly,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And write a deed of gift with thine own blood;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  For that security craves great Lucifer.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  If thou deny it, I will back to hell.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Stay, Mephistophilis, and tell me, what good will my soul\n<br>Â Â Â Â  do thy lord?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Enlarge his kingdom.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Is that the reason why<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000196\">79</$link> he tempts us thus?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Solamen miseris socios habuisse doloris.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000198\">80</$link>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Why,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000200\">81</$link> have you any pain that torture<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000202\">82</$link> others!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. As great as have the human souls of men.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  But, tell me, Faustus, shall I have thy soul?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And I will be thy slave, and wait on thee,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And give thee more than thou hast wit to ask.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Ay, Mephistophilis, I give it thee.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Then, Faustus,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000204\">83</$link> stab thine arm courageously,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And bind thy soul, that at some certain day\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Great Lucifer may claim it as his own;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And then be thou as great as Lucifer.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. [Stabbing his arm] Lo, Mephistophilis, for love of thee,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I cut mine arm, and with my proper blood\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Assure my soul to be great Lucifer's,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Chief lord and regent of perpetual night!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  View here the blood that trickles from mine arm,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And let it be propitious for my wish.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. But, Faustus, thou must\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Write it in manner of a deed of gift.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Ay, so I will [Writes].Â  But, Mephistophilis,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  My blood congeals, and I can write no more.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. I'll fetch thee fire to dissolve it straight.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exit.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. What might the staying of my blood portend?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Is it unwilling I should write this bill?<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000206\">84</$link>Â Â Â Â  Why streams it not, that I may write afresh?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS GIVES TO THEE HIS SOUL:Â  ah, there it stay'd!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Why shouldst thou not? is not thy soul shine own?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Then write again, FAUSTUS GIVES TO THEE HIS SOUL.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Re-enter MEPHISTOPHILIS with a chafer of coals.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Here's fire; come, Faustus, set it on.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000208\">85</$link>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. So, now the blood begins to clear again;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Now will I make an end immediately.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Writes.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. O, what will not I do to obtain his soul?\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Aside.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Consummatum est; this bill is ended,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And Faustus hath bequeath'd his soul to Lucifer.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  But what is this inscription<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000210\">86</$link> on mine arm?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Homo, fuge:Â  whither should I fly?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  If unto God, he'll throw me<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000212\">87</$link> down to hell.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  My senses are deceiv'd; here's nothing writ:â\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I see it plain; here in this place is writ,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Homo, fuge:Â  yet shall not Faustus fly.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. I'll fetch him somewhat to delight his mind.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Aside, and then exit.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Re-enter MEPHISTOPHILIS with DEVILS, who give crowns\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  and rich apparel to FAUSTUS, dance, and then depart.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Speak, Mephistophilis, what means this show?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Nothing, Faustus, but to delight thy mind withal,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And to shew thee what magic can perform.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. But may I raise up spirits when I please?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Ay, Faustus, and do greater things than these.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Then there's enough for a thousand souls.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Here, Mephistophilis, receive this scroll,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  A deed of gift of body and of soul:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  But yet conditionally that thou perform\n<br>Â Â Â Â  All articles prescrib'd between us both.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Faustus, I swear by hell and Lucifer\n<br>Â Â Â Â  To effect all promises between us made!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Then hear me read them.Â  [Reads] ON THESE CONDITIONS\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FOLLOWING.Â  FIRST, THAT FAUSTUS MAY BE A SPIRIT IN FORM AND\n<br>Â Â Â Â  SUBSTANCE.Â  SECONDLY, THAT MEPHISTOPHILIS SHALL BE HIS SERVANT,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  AND AT HIS COMMAND.Â  THIRDLY, THAT MEPHISTOPHILIS SHALL DO FOR HIM,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  AND BRING HIM WHATSOEVER HE DESIRES.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000214\">88</$link>Â  FOURTHLY, THAT HE SHALL\n<br>Â Â Â Â  BE IN HIS CHAMBER OR HOUSE INVISIBLE.Â  LASTLY, THAT HE SHALL APPEAR\n<br>Â Â Â Â  TO THE SAID JOHN FAUSTUS, AT ALL TIMES, IN WHAT FORM OR SHAPE\n<br>Â Â Â Â  SOEVER HE PLEASE.Â  I, JOHN FAUSTUS, OF WERTENBERG, DOCTOR, BY\n<br>Â Â Â Â  THESE PRESENTS, DO GIVE BOTH BODY AND SOUL TO LUCIFER PRINCE OF\n<br>Â Â Â Â  THE EAST, AND HIS MINISTER MEPHISTOPHILIS; AND FURTHERMORE GRANT\n<br>Â Â Â Â  UNTO THEM, THAT,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000216\">89</$link> TWENTY-FOUR YEARS BEING EXPIRED, THE ARTICLES\n<br>Â Â Â Â  ABOVE-WRITTEN INVIOLATE, FULL POWER TO FETCH OR CARRY THE SAID\n<br>Â Â Â Â  JOHN FAUSTUS, BODY AND SOUL, FLESH, BLOOD, OR GOODS, INTO THEIR\n<br>Â Â Â Â  HABITATION WHERESOEVER.Â  BY ME, JOHN FAUSTUS.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Speak, Faustus, do you deliver this as your deed?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Ay, take it, and the devil give thee good on't!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Now, Faustus, ask what thou wilt.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. First will I question with thee about hell.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Tell me, where is the place that men call hell?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Under the heavens.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Ay, but whereabout?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Within the bowels of these<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000218\">90</$link> elements,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Where we are tortur'd and remain for ever:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Hell hath no limits, nor is circumscrib'd\n<br>Â Â Â Â  In one self place; for where we are is hell,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And where hell is, there<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000220\">91</$link> must we ever be:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And, to conclude, when all the world dissolves,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And every creature shall be purified,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  All places shall be hell that are<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000222\">92</$link> not heaven.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Come, I think hell's a fable.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Ay, think so still, till experience change thy mind.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Why, think'st thou, then, that Faustus shall be damn'd?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Ay, of necessity, for here's the scroll\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Wherein thou hast given thy soul to Lucifer.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Ay, and body too:Â  but what of that?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Think'st thou that Faustus is so fond<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000224\">93</$link> to imagine\n<br>Â Â Â Â  That, after this life, there is any pain?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Tush, these are trifles and mere old wives' tales.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. But, Faustus, I am an instance to prove the contrary,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  For I am damn'd, and am now in hell.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. How! now in hell!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Nay, an this be hell, I'll willingly be damn'd here:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  What! walking, disputing, &amp;c.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000226\">94</$link>Â Â Â Â  But, leaving off this, let me have a wife,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000228\">95</$link>Â Â Â Â  The fairest maid in Germany;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  For I am wanton and lascivious,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And cannot live without a wife.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. How! a wife!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I prithee, Faustus, talk not of a wife.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Nay, sweet Mephistophilis, fetch me one, for I will have\n<br>Â Â Â Â  one.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Well, thou wilt have one?Â  Sit there till I come:Â  I'll\n<br>Â Â Â Â  fetch thee a wife in the devil's name.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exit.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Re-enter MEPHISTOPHILIS with a DEVIL drest like a WOMAN,\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  with fire-works.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Tell me,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000230\">96</$link> Faustus, how dost thou like thy wife?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. A plague on her for a hot whore!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Tut, Faustus,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Marriage is but a ceremonial toy;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  If thou lovest me, think no<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000232\">97</$link> more of it.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I'll cull thee out the fairest courtezans,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And bring them every morning to thy bed:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  She whom thine eye shall like, thy heart shall have,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Be she as chaste as was Penelope,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  As wise as Saba,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000234\">98</$link> or as beautiful\n<br>Â Â Â Â  As was bright Lucifer before his fall.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Hold, take this book, peruse it thoroughly:\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Gives book.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  The iterating<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000236\">99</$link> of these lines brings gold;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  The framing of this circle on the ground\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Brings whirlwinds, tempests, thunder, and lightning;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Pronounce this thrice devoutly to thyself,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And men in armour shall appear to thee,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Ready to execute what thou desir'st.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Thanks, Mephistophilis:Â  yet fain would I have a book\n<br>Â Â Â Â  wherein I might behold all spells and incantations, that I\n<br>Â Â Â Â  might raise up spirits when I please.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Here they are in this book.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Turns to them.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Now would I have a book where I might see all characters\n<br>Â Â Â Â  and planets of the heavens, that I might know their motions and\n<br>Â Â Â Â  dispositions.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Here they are too.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Turns to them.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Nay, let me have one book more,âand then I have done,â\n<br>Â Â Â Â  wherein I might see all plants, herbs, and trees, that grow upon\n<br>Â Â Â Â  the earth.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Here they be.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. O, thou art deceived.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Tut, I warrant thee.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Turns to them.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. When I behold the heavens, then I repent,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And curse thee, wicked Mephistophilis,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Because thou hast depriv'd me of those joys.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Why, Faustus,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Thinkest thou heaven is such a glorious thing?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I tell thee, 'tis not half so fair as thou,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Or any man that breathes on earth.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. How prov'st thou that?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. 'Twas made for man, therefore is man more excellent.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. If it were made for man, 'twas made for me:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I will renounce this magic and repent.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter GOOD ANGEL and EVIL ANGEL.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  GOOD ANGEL. Faustus, repent; yet God will pity thee.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  EVIL ANGEL. Thou art a spirit; God cannot pity thee.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Who buzzeth in mine ears I am a spirit?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Be I a devil, yet God may pity me;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Ay, God will pity me, if I repent.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  EVIL ANGEL. Ay, but Faustus never shall repent.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exeunt ANGELS.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. My heart's so harden'd, I cannot repent:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Scarce can I name salvation, faith, or heaven,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  But fearful echoes thunder in mine ears,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  &quot;Faustus, thou art damn'd!&quot; then swords, and knives,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Poison, guns, halters, and envenom'd steel\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Are laid before me to despatch myself;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And long ere this I should have slain myself,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Had not sweet pleasure conquer'd deep despair.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Have not I made blind Homer sing to me\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Of Alexander's love and Oenon's death?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And hath not he, that built the walls of Thebes\n<br>Â Â Â Â  With ravishing sound of his melodious harp,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Made music with my Mephistophilis?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Why should I die, then, or basely despair?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I am resolv'd; Faustus shall ne'er repent.â\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Come, Mephistophilis, let us dispute again,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And argue of divine astrology.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000238\">100</$link>Â Â Â Â  Tell me, are there many heavens above the moon\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Are all celestial bodies but one globe,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  As is the substance of this centric earth?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. As are the elements, such are the spheres,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Mutually folded in each other's orb,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And, Faustus,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  All jointly move upon one axletree,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Whose terminine is term'd the world's wide pole;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Nor are the names of Saturn, Mars, or Jupiter\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Feign'd, but are erring<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000240\">101</$link> stars.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. But, tell me, have they all one motion, both situ et\n<br>Â Â Â Â  tempore?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. All jointly move from east to west in twenty-four hours\n<br>Â Â Â Â  upon the poles of the world; but differ in their motion upon\n<br>Â Â Â Â  the poles of the zodiac.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Tush,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  These slender trifles Wagner can decide:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Hath Mephistophilis no greater skill?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Who knows not the double motion of the planets?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  The first is finish'd in a natural day;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  The second thus; as Saturn in thirty years; Jupiter in twelve;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Mars in four; the Sun, Venus, and Mercury in a year; the Moon in\n<br>Â Â Â Â  twenty-eight days.Â  Tush, these are freshmen's<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000242\">102</$link> suppositions.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  But, tell me, hath every sphere a dominion or intelligentia?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Ay.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. How many heavens or spheres are there?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Nine; the seven planets, the firmament, and the empyreal\n<br>Â Â Â Â  heaven.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Well, resolve<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000244\">103</$link> me in this question; why have we not\n<br>Â Â Â Â  conjunctions, oppositions, aspects, eclipses, all at one time,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  but in some years we have more, in some less?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Per inoequalem motum respectu totius.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Well, I am answered.Â  Tell me who made the world?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. I will not.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Sweet Mephistophilis, tell me.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Move me not, for I will not tell thee.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Villain, have I not bound thee to tell me any thing?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Ay, that is not against our kingdom; but this is.Â  Think\n<br>Â Â Â Â  thou on hell, Faustus, for thou art damned.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Think, Faustus, upon God that made the world.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Remember this.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exit.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Ay, go, accursed spirit, to ugly hell!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  'Tis thou hast damn'd distressed Faustus' soul.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Is't not too late?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Re-enter GOOD ANGEL and EVIL ANGEL.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  EVIL ANGEL. Too late.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  GOOD ANGEL. Never too late, if Faustus can repent.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  EVIL ANGEL. If thou repent, devils shall tear thee in pieces.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  GOOD ANGEL. Repent, and they shall never raze thy skin.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exeunt ANGELS.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Ah, Christ, my Saviour,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Seek to save<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000246\">104</$link> distressed Faustus' soul!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter LUCIFER, BELZEBUB, and MEPHISTOPHILIS.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  LUCIFER. Christ cannot save thy soul, for he is just:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  There's none but I have interest in the same.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. O, who art thou that look'st so terrible?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  LUCIFER. I am Lucifer,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And this is my companion-prince in hell.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. O, Faustus, they are come to fetch away thy soul!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  LUCIFER. We come to tell thee thou dost injure us;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Thou talk'st of Christ, contrary to thy promise:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Thou shouldst not think of God:Â  think of the devil,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And of his dam too.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Nor will I henceforth:Â  pardon me in this,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And Faustus vows never to look to heaven,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Never to name God, or to pray to him,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  To burn his Scriptures, slay his ministers,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And make my spirits pull his churches down.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  LUCIFER. Do so, and we will highly gratify thee.Â  Faustus, we are\n<br>Â Â Â Â  come from hell to shew thee some pastime:Â  sit down, and thou\n<br>Â Â Â Â  shalt see all the Seven Deadly Sins appear in their proper shapes.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. That sight will be as pleasing unto me,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  As Paradise was to Adam, the first day\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Of his creation.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  LUCIFER. Talk not of Paradise nor creation; but mark this show:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  talk of the devil, and nothing else.âCome away!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter the SEVEN DEADLY SINS.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000249\">105</$link>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Now, Faustus, examine them of their several names and dispositions.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. What art thou, the first?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  PRIDE. I am Pride.Â  I disdain to have any parents.Â  I am like to\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Ovid's flea; I can creep into every corner of a wench; sometimes,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  like a perriwig, I sit upon her brow; or, like a fan of feathers,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I kiss her lips; indeed, I doâwhat do I not?Â  But, fie, what a\n<br>Â Â Â Â  scent is here!Â  I'll not speak another word, except the ground\n<br>Â Â Â Â  were perfumed, and covered with cloth of arras.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. What art thou, the second?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  COVETOUSNESS. I am Covetousness, begotten of an old churl, in an\n<br>Â Â Â Â  old leathern bag:Â  and, might I have my wish, I would desire that\n<br>Â Â Â Â  this house and all the people in it were turned to gold, that I\n<br>Â Â Â Â  might lock you up in my good chest:Â  O, my sweet gold!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. What art thou, the third?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WRATH. I am Wrath.Â  I had neither father nor mother:Â  I leapt out\n<br>Â Â Â Â  of a lion's mouth when I was scarce half-an-hour old; and ever\n<br>Â Â Â Â  since I have run up and down the world with this case<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000251\">106</$link>Â Â Â Â  of rapiers, wounding myself when I had nobody to fight withal.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I was born in hell; and look to it, for some of you shall be\n<br>Â Â Â Â  my father.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. What art thou, the fourth?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  ENVY. I am Envy, begotten of a chimney-sweeper and an oyster-wife.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I cannot read, and therefore wish all books were burnt.Â  I am lean\n<br>Â Â Â Â  with seeing others eat.Â  O, that there would come a famine through\n<br>Â Â Â Â  all the world, that all might die, and I live alone! then thou\n<br>Â Â Â Â  shouldst see how fat I would be.Â  But must thou sit, and I stand?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  come down, with a vengeance!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Away, envious rascal!âWhat art thou, the fifth?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  GLUTTONY. Who I, sir?Â  I am Gluttony.Â  My parents are all dead,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  and the devil a penny they have left me, but a bare pension, and\n<br>Â Â Â Â  that is thirty meals a-day and ten bevers,</div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000031": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000031",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-65fb807d23063af6-7a2b93 twpub-65fb807d23063af6-de533d twpub-65fb807d23063af6-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"pgmonospaced\"><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000253\">107</$link>âa small trifle\n<br>Â Â Â Â  to suffice nature.Â  O, I come of a royal parentage! my grandfather\n<br>Â Â Â Â  was a Gammon of Bacon, my grandmother a Hogshead of Claret-wine;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  my godfathers were these, Peter Pickle-herring and Martin\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Martlemas-beef; O, but my godmother, she was a jolly gentlewoman,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  and well-beloved in every good town and city; her name was Mistress\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Margery March-beer.Â  Now, Faustus, thou hast heard all my progeny;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  wilt thou bid me to supper?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. No, I'll see thee hanged:Â  thou wilt eat up all my victuals.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  GLUTTONY. Then the devil choke thee!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Choke thyself, glutton!âWhat art thou, the sixth?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  SLOTH. I am Sloth.Â  I was begotten on a sunny bank, where I have\n<br>Â Â Â Â  lain ever since; and you have done me great injury to bring me\n<br>Â Â Â Â  from thence:Â  let me be carried thither again by Gluttony and\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Lechery.Â  I'll not speak another word for a king's ransom.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. What are you, Mistress Minx, the seventh and last?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  LECHERY. Who I, sir?Â  I am one that loves an inch of raw mutton\n<br>Â Â Â Â  better than an ell of fried stock-fish; and the first letter\n<br>Â Â Â Â  of my name begins with L.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000255\">108</$link>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Away, to hell, to hell!<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000257\">109</$link>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exeunt the SINS.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  LUCIFER. Now, Faustus, how dost thou like this?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. O, this feeds my soul!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  LUCIFER. Tut, Faustus, in hell is all manner of delight.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. O, might I see hell, and return again,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  How happy were I then!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  LUCIFER. Thou shalt; I will send for thee at midnight.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000260\">110</$link>Â Â Â Â  In meantime take this book; peruse it throughly,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And thou shalt turn thyself into what shape thou wilt.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Great thanks, mighty Lucifer!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  This will I keep as chary as my life.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  LUCIFER. Farewell, Faustus, and think on the devil.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Farewell, great Lucifer.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exeunt LUCIFER and BELZEBUB.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Come, Mephistophilis.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exeunt.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter CHORUS.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000262\">111</$link>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CHORUS. Learned Faustus,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  To know the secrets of astronomy<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000264\">112</$link>Â Â Â Â  Graven in the book of Jove's high firmament,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Did mount himself to scale Olympus' top,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Being seated in a chariot burning bright,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Drawn by the strength of yoky dragons' necks.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  He now is gone to prove cosmography,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And, as I guess, will first arrive at Rome,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  To see the Pope and manner of his court,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And take some part of holy Peter's feast,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  That to this day is highly solemniz'd.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exit.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter FAUSTUS and MEPHISTOPHILIS.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000266\">113</$link>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Having now, my good Mephistophilis,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Pass'd with delight the stately town of Trier,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000268\">114</$link>Â Â Â Â  Environ'd round with airy mountain-tops,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  With walls of flint, and deep-entrenched lakes,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Not to be won by any conquering prince;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  From Paris next,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000270\">115</$link> coasting the realm of France,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  We saw the river Maine fall into Rhine,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Whose banks are set with groves of fruitful vines;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Then up to Naples, rich Campania,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Whose buildings fair and gorgeous to the eye,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  The streets straight forth, and pav'd with finest brick,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Quarter the town in four equivalents:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  There saw we learned Maro's golden tomb,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  The way he cut,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000272\">116</$link> an English mile in length,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Thorough a rock of stone, in one night's space;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  From thence to Venice, Padua, and the rest,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  In one of which a sumptuous temple stands,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000274\">117</$link>Â Â Â Â  That threats the stars with her aspiring top.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Thus hitherto hath Faustus spent his time:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  But tell me now what resting-place is this?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Hast thou, as erst I did command,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Conducted me within the walls of Rome?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Faustus, I have; and, because we will not be unprovided,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I have taken up his Holiness' privy-chamber for our use.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. I hope his Holiness will bid us welcome.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Tut, 'tis no matter; man; we'll be bold with his good cheer.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And now, my Faustus, that thou mayst perceive\n<br>Â Â Â Â  What Rome containeth to delight thee with,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Know that this city stands upon seven hills\n<br>Â Â Â Â  That underprop the groundwork of the same:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Just through the midst<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000276\">118</$link> runs flowing Tiber's stream\n<br>Â Â Â Â  With winding banks that cut it in two parts;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Over the which four stately bridges lean,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  That make safe passage to each part of Rome:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Upon the bridge call'd Ponte<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000278\">119</$link> Angelo\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Erected is a castle passing strong,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Within whose walls such store of ordnance are,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And double cannons fram'd of carved brass,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  As match the days within one complete year;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Besides the gates, and high pyramides,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Which Julius Caesar brought from Africa.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Now, by the kingdoms of infernal rule,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Of Styx, of<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000280\">120</$link> Acheron, and the fiery lake\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Of ever-burning Phlegethon, I swear\n<br>Â Â Â Â  That I do long to see the monuments\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And situation of bright-splendent Rome:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Come, therefore, let's away.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Nay, Faustus, stay:Â  I know you'd fain see the Pope,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And take some part of holy Peter's feast,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Where thou shalt see a troop of bald-pate friars,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Whose summum bonum is in belly-cheer.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Well, I'm content to compass then some sport,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And by their folly make us merriment.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Then charm me, that I<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000282\">121</$link>Â Â Â Â  May be invisible, to do what I please,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Unseen of any whilst I stay in Rome.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Mephistophilis charms him.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. So, Faustus; now\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Do what thou wilt, thou shalt not be discern'd.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Sound a Sonnet.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000284\">122</$link> Enter the POPE and the CARDINAL OF\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  LORRAIN to the banquet, with FRIARS attending.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  POPE. My Lord of Lorrain, will't please you draw near?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Fall to, and the devil choke you, an you spare!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  POPE. How now! who's that which spake?âFriars, look about.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FIRST FRIAR. Here's nobody, if it like your Holiness.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  POPE. My lord, here is a dainty dish was sent me from the Bishop\n<br>Â Â Â Â  of Milan.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. I thank you, sir.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Snatches the dish.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  POPE. How now! who's that which snatched the meat from me? will\n<br>Â Â Â Â  no man look?âMy lord, this dish was sent me from the Cardinal\n<br>Â Â Â Â  of Florence.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. You say true; I'll ha't.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Snatches the dish.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  POPE. What, again!âMy lord, I'll drink to your grace.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. I'll pledge your grace.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Snatches the cup.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  C. OF LOR. My lord, it may be some ghost, newly crept out of\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Purgatory, come to beg a pardon of your Holiness.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  POPE. It may be so.âFriars, prepare a dirge to lay the fury\n<br>Â Â Â Â  of this ghost.âOnce again, my lord, fall to.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [The POPE crosses himself.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. What, are you crossing of yourself?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Well, use that trick no more, I would advise you.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [The POPE crosses himself again.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Well, there's the second time.Â  Aware the third;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I give you fair warning.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [The POPE crosses himself again, and FAUSTUS hits him a box\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  of the ear; and they all run away.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Come on, Mephistophilis; what shall we do?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Nay, I know not:Â  we shall be cursed with bell, book,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  and candle.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. How! bell, book, and candle,âcandle, book, and bell,â\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Forward and backward, to curse Faustus to hell!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Anon you shall hear a hog grunt, a calf bleat, and an ass bray,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Because it is Saint Peter's holiday.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Re-enter all the FRIARS to sing the Dirge.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FIRST FRIAR.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Come, brethren, let's about our business with good devotion.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  They sing.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CURSED BE HE THAT STOLE AWAY HIS HOLINESS' MEAT FROM THE\n<br>Â Â Â Â  TABLE!Â  maledicat Dominus!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CURSED BE HE THAT STRUCK HIS HOLINESS A BLOW ON THE FACE!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  maledicat Dominus!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CURSED BE HE THAT TOOK FRIAR SANDELO A BLOW ON THE PATE!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  maledicat Dominus!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CURSED BE HE THAT DISTURBETH OUR HOLY DIRGE!Â  maledicat\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Dominus!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CURSED BE HE THAT TOOK AWAY HIS HOLINESS' WINE!Â  maledicat\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Dominus?Â  ['?' sic]\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Et omnes Sancti!Â  Amen!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [MEPHISTOPHILIS and FAUSTUS beat the FRIARS, and fling\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  fire-works among them; and so exeunt.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter CHORUS.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CHORUS. When Faustus had with pleasure ta'en the view\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Of rarest things, and royal courts of kings,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  He stay'd his course, and so returned home;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Where such as bear his absence but with grief,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I mean his friends and near'st companions,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Did gratulate his safety with kind words,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And in their conference of what befell,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Touching his journey through the world and air,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  They put forth questions of astrology,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Which Faustus answer'd with such learned skill\n<br>Â Â Â Â  As they admir'd and wonder'd at his wit.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Now is his fame spread forth in every land:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Amongst the rest the Emperor is one,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Carolus the Fifth, at whose palace now\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Faustus is feasted 'mongst his noblemen.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  What there he did, in trial of his art,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I leave untold; your eyes shall see['t] perform'd.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exit.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter ROBIN<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000286\">123</$link> the Ostler, with a book in his hand.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  ROBIN. O, this is admirable! here I ha' stolen one of Doctor\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Faustus' conjuring-books, and, i'faith, I mean to search some\n<br>Â Â Â Â  circles for my own use.Â  Now will I make all the maidens in our\n<br>Â Â Â Â  parish dance at my pleasure, stark naked, before me; and so\n<br>Â Â Â Â  by that means I shall see more than e'er I felt or saw yet.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter RALPH, calling ROBIN.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  RALPH. Robin, prithee, come away; there's a gentleman tarries\n<br>Â Â Â Â  to have his horse, and he would have his things rubbed and made\n<br>Â Â Â Â  clean:Â  he keeps such a chafing with my mistress about it; and\n<br>Â Â Â Â  she has sent me to look thee out; prithee, come away.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  ROBIN. Keep out, keep out, or else you are blown up, you are\n<br>Â Â Â Â  dismembered, Ralph:Â  keep out, for I am about a roaring piece\n<br>Â Â Â Â  of work.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  RALPH. Come, what doest thou with that same book? thou canst\n<br>Â Â Â Â  not read?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  ROBIN. Yes, my master and mistress shall find that I can read,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  he for his forehead, she for her private study; she's born to\n<br>Â Â Â Â  bear with me, or else my art fails.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  RALPH. Why, Robin, what book is that?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  ROBIN. What book! why, the most intolerable book for conjuring\n<br>Â Â Â Â  that e'er was invented by any brimstone devil.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  RALPH. Canst thou conjure with it?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  ROBIN. I can do all these things easily with it; first, I can\n<br>Â Â Â Â  make thee drunk with ippocras<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000288\">124</$link> at any tabern<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000290\">125</$link> in Europe\n<br>Â Â Â Â  for nothing; that's one of my conjuring works.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  RALPH. Our Master Parson says that's nothing.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  ROBIN. True, Ralph:Â  and more, Ralph, if thou hast any mind to\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Nan Spit, our kitchen-maid, then turn her and wind her to thy own\n<br>Â Â Â Â  use, as often as thou wilt, and at midnight.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  RALPH. O, brave, Robin! shall I have Nan Spit, and to mine own\n<br>Â Â Â Â  use?Â  On that condition I'll feed thy devil with horse-bread as\n<br>Â Â Â Â  long as he lives, of free cost.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  ROBIN. No more, sweet Ralph:Â  let's go and make clean our boots,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  which lie foul upon our hands, and then to our conjuring in the\n<br>Â Â Â Â  devil's name.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exeunt.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter ROBIN and RALPH<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000292\">126</$link> with a silver goblet.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  ROBIN. Come, Ralph:Â  did not I tell thee, we were for ever made\n<br>Â Â Â Â  by this Doctor Faustus' book? ecce, signum! here's a simple\n<br>Â Â Â Â  purchase<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000294\">127</$link> for horse-keepers:Â  our horses shall eat no hay as\n<br>Â Â Â Â  long as this lasts.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  RALPH. But, Robin, here comes the Vintner.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  ROBIN. Hush!Â  I'll gull him supernaturally.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter VINTNER.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Drawer,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000296\">128</$link> I hope all is paid; God be with you!âCome, Ralph.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  VINTNER. Soft, sir; a word with you.Â  I must yet have a goblet paid\n<br>Â Â Â Â  from you, ere you go.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  ROBIN. I a goblet, Ralph, I a goblet!âI scorn you; and you are\n<br>Â Â Â Â  but a, &amp;c.Â  I a goblet! search me.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  VINTNER. I mean so, sir, with your favour.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Searches ROBIN.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  ROBIN. How say you now?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  VINTNER. I must say somewhat to your fellow.âYou, sir!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  RALPH. Me, sir! me, sir! search your fill.Â  [VINTNER searches him.]\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Now, sir, you may be ashamed to burden honest men with a matter\n<br>Â Â Â Â  of truth.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  VINTNER. Well, tone<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000298\">129</$link> of you hath this goblet about you.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  ROBIN. You lie, drawer, 'tis afore me [Aside].âSirrah you, I'll\n<br>Â Â Â Â  teach you to impeach honest men;âstand by;âI'll scour you for\n<br>Â Â Â Â  a goblet;âstand aside you had best, I charge you in the name of\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Belzebub.âLook to the goblet, Ralph [Aside to RALPH].\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  VINTNER. What mean you, sirrah?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  ROBIN. I'll tell you what I mean.Â  [Reads from a book] Sanctobulorum\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Periphrasticonânay, I'll tickle you, Vintner.âLook to the goblet,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Ralph [Aside to RALPH].â[Reads] Polypragmos Belseborams framanto\n<br>Â Â Â Â  pacostiphos tostu, Mephistophilis, &amp;c.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter MEPHISTOPHILIS, sets squibs at their backs, and then\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  exit.Â  They run about.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  VINTNER. O, nomine Domini! what meanest thou, Robin? thou hast no\n<br>Â Â Â Â  goblet.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  RALPH. Peccatum peccatorum!âHere's thy goblet, good Vintner.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Gives the goblet to VINTNER, who exit.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  ROBIN. Misericordia pro nobis! what shall I do?Â  Good devil, forgive\n<br>Â Â Â Â  me now, and I'll never rob thy library more.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Re-enter MEPHISTOPHILIS.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Monarch of Hell,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000300\">130</$link> under whose black survey\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Great potentates do kneel with awful fear,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Upon whose altars thousand souls do lie,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  How am I vexed with these villains' charms?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  From Constantinople am I hither come,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Only for pleasure of these damned slaves.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  ROBIN. How, from Constantinople! you have had a great journey:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  will you take sixpence in your purse to pay for your supper, and\n<br>Â Â Â Â  be gone?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Well, villains, for your presumption, I transform thee\n<br>Â Â Â Â  into an ape, and thee into a dog; and so be gone!\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exit.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  ROBIN. How, into an ape! that's brave:Â  I'll have fine sport with\n<br>Â Â Â Â  the boys; I'll get nuts and apples enow.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  RALPH. And I must be a dog.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  ROBIN. I'faith, thy head will never be out of the pottage-pot.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exeunt.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter EMPEROR,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000304\">131</$link> FAUSTUS, and a KNIGHT, with ATTENDANTS.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  EMPEROR. Master Doctor Faustus,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000306\">132</$link> I have heard strange report\n<br>Â Â Â Â  of thy knowledge in the black art, how that none in my empire\n<br>Â Â Â Â  nor in the whole world can compare with thee for the rare effects\n<br>Â Â Â Â  of magic:Â  they say thou hast a familiar spirit, by whom thou canst\n<br>Â Â Â Â  accomplish what thou list.Â  This, therefore, is my request, that\n<br>Â Â Â Â  thou let me see some proof of thy skill, that mine eyes may be\n<br>Â Â Â Â  witnesses to confirm what mine ears have heard reported:Â  and here\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I swear to thee, by the honour of mine imperial crown, that,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  whatever thou doest, thou shalt be no ways prejudiced or endamaged.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  KNIGHT. I'faith, he looks much like a conjurer.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Aside.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. My gracious sovereign, though I must confess myself far\n<br>Â Â Â Â  inferior to the report men have published, and nothing answerable\n<br>Â Â Â Â  to the honour of your imperial majesty, yet, for that love and duty\n<br>Â Â Â Â  binds me thereunto, I am content to do whatsoever your majesty\n<br>Â Â Â Â  shall command me.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  EMPEROR. Then, Doctor Faustus, mark what I shall say.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  As I was sometime solitary set\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Within my closet, sundry thoughts arose\n<br>Â Â Â Â  About the honour of mine ancestors,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  How they had won<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000308\">133</$link> by prowess such exploits,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Got such riches, subdu'd so many kingdoms,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  As we that do succeed,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000310\">134</$link> or they that shall\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Hereafter possess our throne, shall\n<br>Â Â Â Â  (I fear me) ne'er attain to that degree\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Of high renown and great authority:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Amongst which kings is Alexander the Great,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Chief spectacle of the world's pre-eminence,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  The bright<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000312\">135</$link> shining of whose glorious acts\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Lightens the world with his reflecting beams,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  As when I hear but motion made of him,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  It grieves my soul I never saw the man:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  If, therefore, thou, by cunning of thine art,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Canst raise this man from hollow vaults below,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Where lies entomb'd this famous conqueror,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And bring with him his beauteous paramour,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Both in their right shapes, gesture, and attire\n<br>Â Â Â Â  They us'd to wear during their time of life,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Thou shalt both satisfy my just desire,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And give me cause to praise thee whilst I live.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. My gracious lord, I am ready to accomplish your request,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  so far forth as by art and power of my spirit I am able to perform.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  KNIGHT. I'faith, that's just nothing at all.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Aside.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. But, if it like your grace, it is not in my ability<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000315\">136</$link>Â Â Â Â  to present before your eyes the true substantial bodies of those\n<br>Â Â Â Â  two deceased princes, which long since are consumed to dust.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  KNIGHT. Ay, marry, Master Doctor, now there's a sign of grace in\n<br>Â Â Â Â  you, when you will confess the truth.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Aside.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. But such spirits as can lively resemble Alexander and\n<br>Â Â Â Â  his paramour shall appear before your grace, in that manner that\n<br>Â Â Â Â  they both<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000317\">137</$link> lived in, in their most flourishing estate; which\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I doubt not shall sufficiently content your imperial majesty.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  EMPEROR. Go to, Master Doctor; let me see them presently.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  KNIGHT. Do you hear, Master Doctor? you bring Alexander and his\n<br>Â Â Â Â  paramour before the Emperor!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. How then, sir?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  KNIGHT. I'faith, that's as true as Diana turned me to a stag.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. No, sir; but, when Actaeon died, he left the horns for\n<br>Â Â Â Â  you.âMephistophilis, be gone.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exit MEPHISTOPHILIS.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  KNIGHT. Nay, an you go to conjuring, I'll be gone.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exit.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. I'll meet with you anon for interrupting me so.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  âHere they are, my gracious lord.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Re-enter MEPHISTOPHILIS with SPIRITS in the shapes of ALEXANDER\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  and his PARAMOUR.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  EMPEROR. Master Doctor, I heard this lady, while she lived, had a\n<br>Â Â Â Â  wart or mole in her neck:Â  how shall I know whether it be so or no?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Your highness may boldly go and see.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  EMPEROR. Sure, these are no spirits, but the true substantial\n<br>Â Â Â Â  bodies of those two deceased princes.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exeunt Spirits.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Wilt please your highness now to send for the knight\n<br>Â Â Â Â  that was so pleasant with me here of late?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  EMPEROR. One of you call him forth.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exit ATTENDANT.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Re-enter the KNIGHT with a pair of horns on his head.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  How now, sir knight! why, I had thought thou hadst been a bachelor,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  but now I see thou hast a wife, that not only gives thee horns,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  but makes thee wear them.Â  Feel on thy head.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  KNIGHT. Thou damned wretch and execrable dog,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Bred in the concave of some monstrous rock,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  How dar'st thou thus abuse a gentleman?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Villain, I say, undo what thou hast done!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. O, not so fast, sir! there's no haste:Â  but, good, are\n<br>Â Â Â Â  you remembered how you crossed me in my conference with the\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Emperor?Â  I think I have met with you for it.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  EMPEROR. Good Master Doctor, at my entreaty release him:Â  he hath\n<br>Â Â Â Â  done penance sufficient.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. My gracious lord, not so much for the injury he offered\n<br>Â Â Â Â  me here in your presence, as to delight you with some mirth, hath\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Faustus worthily requited this injurious knight; which being all\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I desire, I am content to release him of his horns:âand,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  sir knight, hereafter speak well of scholars.âMephistophilis,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  transform him straight.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000319\">138</$link>Â  [MEPHISTOPHILIS removes the horns.]\n<br>Â Â Â Â  âNow, my good lord, having done my duty, I humbly take my leave.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  EMPEROR. Farewell, Master Doctor:Â  yet, ere you go,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Expect from me a bounteous reward.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exeunt EMPEROR, KNIGHT, and ATTENDANTS.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Now, Mephistophilis,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000321\">139</$link> the restless course\n<br>Â Â Â Â  That time doth run with calm and silent foot,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Shortening my days and thread of vital life,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Calls for the payment of my latest years:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Therefore, sweet Mephistophilis, let us\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Make haste to Wertenberg.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. What, will you go on horse-back or on foot[?]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Nay, till I'm past this fair and pleasant green,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I'll walk on foot.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter a HORSE-COURSER.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000323\">140</$link>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  HORSE-COURSER. I have been all this day seeking one Master Fustian:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  mass, see where he is!âGod save you, Master Doctor!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. What, horse-courser! you are well met.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  HORSE-COURSER. Do you hear, sir?Â  I have brought you forty dollars\n<br>Â Â Â Â  for your horse.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. I cannot sell him so:Â  if thou likest him for fifty, take\n<br>Â Â Â Â  him.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  HORSE-COURSER. Alas, sir, I have no more!âI pray you, speak for\n<br>Â Â Â Â  me.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. I pray you, let him have him:Â  he is an honest fellow,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  and he has a great charge, neither wife nor child.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Well, come, give me your money [HORSE-COURSER gives\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS the money]:Â  my boy will deliver him to you.Â  But I must\n<br>Â Â Â Â  tell you one thing before you have him; ride him not into the\n<br>Â Â Â Â  water, at any hand.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  HORSE-COURSER. Why, sir, will he not drink of all waters?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. O, yes, he will drink of all waters; but ride him not\n<br>Â Â Â Â  into the water:Â  ride him over hedge or ditch, or where thou wilt,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  but not into the water.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  HORSE-COURSER. Well, sir.âNow am I made man for ever:Â  I'll not\n<br>Â Â Â Â  leave my horse for forty:<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000325\">141</$link>Â  if he had but the quality of\n<br>Â Â Â Â  hey-ding-ding, hey-ding-ding, I'd make a brave living on him:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  he has a buttock as slick as an eel [Aside].âWell, God b'wi'ye,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  sir:Â  your boy will deliver him me:Â  but, hark you, sir; if my horse\n<br>Â Â Â Â  be sick or ill at ease, if I bring his water to you, you'll tell\n<br>Â Â Â Â  me what it is?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Away, you villain! what, dost think I am a horse-doctor?\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exit HORSE-COURSER.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  What art thou, Faustus, but a man condemn'd to die?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Thy fatal time doth draw to final end;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Despair doth drive distrust into<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000327\">142</$link> my thoughts:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Confound these passions with a quiet sleep:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Tush, Christ did call the thief upon the Cross;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Then rest thee, Faustus, quiet in conceit.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Sleeps in his chair.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Re-enter HORSE-COURSER, all wet, crying.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  HORSE-COURSER. Alas, alas!Â  Doctor Fustian, quoth a? mass, Doctor\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Lopus<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000329\">143</$link> was never such a doctor:Â  has given me a purgation, has\n<br>Â Â Â Â  purged me of forty dollars; I shall never see them more.Â  But yet,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  like an ass as I was, I would not be ruled by him, for he bade me\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I should ride him into no water:Â  now I, thinking my horse had had\n<br>Â Â Â Â  some rare quality that he would not have had me know of,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000331\">144</$link> I,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  like a venturous youth, rid him into the deep pond at the town's\n<br>Â Â Â Â  end.Â  I was no sooner in the middle of the pond, but my horse\n<br>Â Â Â Â  vanished away, and I sat upon a bottle of hay, never so near\n<br>Â Â Â Â  drowning in my life.Â  But I'll seek out my doctor, and have my\n<br>Â Â Â Â  forty dollars again, or I'll make it the dearest horse!âO,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  yonder is his snipper-snapper.âDo you hear? you, hey-pass,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000333\">145</$link>Â Â Â Â  where's your master?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Why, sir, what would you? you cannot speak with him.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  HORSE-COURSER. But I will speak with him.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Why, he's fast asleep:Â  come some other time.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  HORSE-COURSER. I'll speak with him now, or I'll break his\n<br>Â Â Â Â  glass-windows about his ears.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. I tell thee, he has not slept this eight nights.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  HORSE-COURSER. An he have not slept this eight weeks, I'll\n<br>Â Â Â Â  speak with him.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. See, where he is, fast asleep.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  HORSE-COURSER. Ay, this is he.âGod save you, Master Doctor,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Master Doctor, Master Doctor Fustian! forty dollars, forty dollars\n<br>Â Â Â Â  for a bottle of hay!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Why, thou seest he hears thee not.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  HORSE-COURSER. So-ho, ho! so-ho, ho!Â  [Hollows in his ear.]Â  No,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  will you not wake?Â  I'll make you wake ere I go.Â  [Pulls FAUSTUS\n<br>Â Â Â Â  by the leg, and pulls it away.]Â  Alas, I am undone! what shall\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I do?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. O, my leg, my leg!âHelp, Mephistophilis! call the\n<br>Â Â Â Â  officers.âMy leg, my leg!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Come, villain, to the constable.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  HORSE-COURSER. O Lord, sir, let me go, and I'll give you forty\n<br>Â Â Â Â  dollars more!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Where be they?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  HORSE-COURSER. I have none about me:Â  come to my ostry,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000335\">146</$link>Â Â Â Â  and I'll give them you.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Be gone quickly.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [HORSE-COURSER runs away.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. What, is he gone? farewell he!Â  Faustus has his leg again,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  and the Horse-courser, I take it, a bottle of hay for his labour:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  well, this trick shall cost him forty dollars more.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter WAGNER.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  How now, Wagner! what's the news with thee?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. Sir, the Duke of Vanholt doth earnestly entreat your\n<br>Â Â Â Â  company.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. The Duke of Vanholt! an honourable gentleman, to whom\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I must be no niggard of my cunning.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000337\">147</$link>âCome, Mephistophilis,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  let's away to him.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exeunt.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter the DUKE OF VANHOLT, the DUCHESS, and FAUSTUS.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000339\">148</$link>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  DUKE. Believe me, Master Doctor, this merriment hath much pleased\n<br>Â Â Â Â  me.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. My gracious lord, I am glad it contents you so well.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  âBut it may be, madam, you take no delight in this.Â  I have heard\n<br>Â Â Â Â  that great-bellied women do long for some dainties or other:Â  what\n<br>Â Â Â Â  is it, madam? tell me, and you shall have it.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  DUCHESS. Thanks, good Master Doctor:Â  and, for I see your courteous\n<br>Â Â Â Â  intent to pleasure me, I will not hide from you the thing my heart\n<br>Â Â Â Â  desires; and, were it now summer, as it is January and the dead\n<br>Â Â Â Â  time of the winter, I would desire no better meat than a dish\n<br>Â Â Â Â  of ripe grapes.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Alas, madam, that's nothing!âMephistophilis, be gone.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  [Exit MEPHISTOPHILIS.] Were it a greater thing than this, so it\n<br>Â Â Â Â  would content you, you should have it.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Re-enter MEPHISTOPHILIS with grapes.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Here they be, madam:Â  wilt please you taste on them?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  DUKE. Believe me, Master Doctor, this makes me wonder above the\n<br>Â Â Â Â  rest, that being in the dead time of winter and in the month of\n<br>Â Â Â Â  January, how you should come by these grapes.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. If it like your grace, the year is divided into two\n<br>Â Â Â Â  circles over the whole world, that, when it is here winter with\n<br>Â Â Â Â  us, in the contrary circle it is summer with them, as in India,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Saba,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000343\">149</$link> and farther countries in the east; and by means of a\n<br>Â Â Â Â  swift spirit that I have, I had them brought hither, as you see.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  âHow do you like them, madam? be they good?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  DUCHESS. Believe me, Master Doctor, they be the best grapes that\n<br>Â Â Â Â  e'er I tasted in my life before.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. I am glad they content you so, madam.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  DUKE. Come, madam, let us in, where you must well reward this\n<br>Â Â Â Â  learned man for the great kindness he hath shewed to you.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  DUCHESS. And so I will, my lord; and, whilst I live, rest\n<br>Â Â Â Â  beholding<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000345\">150</$link> for this courtesy.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. I humbly thank your grace.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  DUKE. Come, Master Doctor, follow us, and receive your reward.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exeunt.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter WAGNER.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000347\">151</$link>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  WAGNER. I think my master means to die shortly,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  For he hath given to me all his goods:<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000349\">152</$link>Â Â Â Â  And yet, methinks, if that death were near,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  He would not banquet, and carouse, and swill\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Amongst the students, as even now he doth,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Who are at supper with such belly-cheer\n<br>Â Â Â Â  As Wagner ne'er beheld in all his life.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  See, where they come! belike the feast is ended.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exit.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter FAUSTUS with two or three SCHOLARS, and MEPHISTOPHILIS.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FIRST SCHOLAR. Master Doctor Faustus, since our conference about\n<br>Â Â Â Â  fair ladies, which was the beautifulest in all the world, we have\n<br>Â Â Â Â  determined with ourselves that Helen of Greece was the admirablest\n<br>Â Â Â Â  lady that ever lived:Â  therefore, Master Doctor, if you will do us\n<br>Â Â Â Â  that favour, as to let us see that peerless dame of Greece, whom\n<br>Â Â Â Â  all the world admires for majesty, we should think ourselves much\n<br>Â Â Â Â  beholding unto you.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Gentlemen,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  For that I know your friendship is unfeign'd,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And Faustus' custom is not to deny\n<br>Â Â Â Â  The just requests of those that wish him well,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  You shall behold that peerless dame of Greece,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  No otherways for pomp and majesty\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Than when Sir Paris cross'd the seas with her,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And brought the spoils to rich Dardania.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Be silent, then, for danger is in words.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Music sounds, and HELEN passeth over the stage.] <$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000351\">153</$link>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  SECOND SCHOLAR. Too simple is my wit to tell her praise,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Whom all the world admires for majesty.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  THIRD SCHOLAR. No marvel though the angry Greeks pursu'd\n<br>Â Â Â Â  With ten years' war the rape of such a queen,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Whose heavenly beauty passeth all compare.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FIRST SCHOLAR. Since we have seen the pride of Nature's works,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And only paragon of excellence,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Let us depart; and for this glorious deed\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Happy and blest be Faustus evermore!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Gentlemen, farewell:Â  the same I wish to you.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exeunt SCHOLARS.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter an OLD MAN.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000353\">154</$link>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  OLD MAN. Ah, Doctor Faustus, that I might prevail\n<br>Â Â Â Â  To guide thy steps unto the way of life,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  By which sweet path thou mayst attain the goal\n<br>Â Â Â Â  That shall conduct thee to celestial rest!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Break heart, drop blood, and mingle it with tears,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Tears falling from repentant heaviness\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Of thy most vile<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000355\">155</$link> and loathsome filthiness,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  The stench whereof corrupts the inward soul\n<br>Â Â Â Â  With such flagitious crimes of heinous sin<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000358\">156</$link>Â Â Â Â  As no commiseration may expel,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  But mercy, Faustus, of thy Saviour sweet,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Whose blood alone must wash away thy guilt.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Where art thou, Faustus? wretch, what hast thou done?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Damn'd art thou, Faustus, damn'd; despair and die!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Hell calls for right, and with a roaring voice\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Says, &quot;Faustus, come; thine hour is almost<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000360\">157</$link> come;&quot;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And Faustus now<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000362\">158</$link> will come to do thee right.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [MEPHISTOPHILIS gives him a dagger.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  OLD MAN. Ah, stay, good Faustus, stay thy desperate steps!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I see an angel hovers o'er thy head,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And, with a vial full of precious grace,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Offers to pour the same into thy soul:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Then call for mercy, and avoid despair.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Ah, my sweet friend, I feel\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Thy words to comfort my distressed soul!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Leave me a while to ponder on my sins.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  OLD MAN. I go, sweet Faustus; but with heavy cheer,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Fearing the ruin of thy hopeless soul.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exit.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Accursed Faustus, where is mercy now?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I do repent; and yet I do despair:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Hell strives with grace for conquest in my breast:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  What shall I do to shun the snares of death?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Thou traitor, Faustus, I arrest thy soul\n<br>Â Â Â Â  For disobedience to my sovereign lord:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Revolt, or I'll in piece-meal tear thy flesh.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Sweet Mephistophilis, entreat thy lord\n<br>Â Â Â Â  To pardon my unjust presumption,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And with my blood again I will confirm\n<br>Â Â Â Â  My former vow I made to Lucifer.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Do it, then, quickly,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000364\">159</$link> with unfeigned heart,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Lest greater danger do attend thy drift.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Torment, sweet friend, that base and crooked age,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  That durst dissuade me from thy Lucifer,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  With greatest torments that our hell affords.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. His faith is great; I cannot touch his soul;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  But what I may afflict his body with\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I will attempt, which is but little worth.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. One thing, good servant,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000366\">160</$link> let me crave of thee,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  To glut the longing of my heart's desire,â\n<br>Â Â Â Â  That I might have unto my paramour\n<br>Â Â Â Â  That heavenly Helen which I saw of late,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Whose sweet embracings may extinguish clean\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Those<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000368\">161</$link> thoughts that do dissuade me from my vow,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And keep mine oath I made to Lucifer.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  MEPHIST. Faustus, this,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000370\">162</$link> or what else thou shalt desire,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Shall be perform'd in twinkling of an eye.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Re-enter HELEN.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Was this the face that launch'd a thousand ships,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And burnt the topless<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000372\">163</$link> towers of Iliumâ\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Sweet Helen, make me immortal with a kiss.â\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Kisses her.]\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Her lips suck forth my soul:Â  see, where it flies!â\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Come, Helen, come, give me my soul again.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Here will I dwell, for heaven is<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000374\">164</$link> in these lips,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And all is dross that is not Helena.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I will be Paris, and for love of thee,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Instead of Troy, shall Wertenberg be sack'd;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And I will combat with weak Menelaus,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And wear thy colours on my plumed crest;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Yea, I will wound Achilles in the heel,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And then return to Helen for a kiss.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  O, thou art fairer than the evening air\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Clad in the beauty of a thousand stars;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Brighter art thou than flaming Jupiter\n<br>Â Â Â Â  When he appear'd to hapless Semele;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  More lovely than the monarch of the sky\n<br>Â Â Â Â  In wanton Arethusa's azur'd arms;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And none but thou shalt<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000376\">165</$link> be my paramour!\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exeunt.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter the OLD MAN.<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000378\">166</$link>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  OLD MAN. Accursed Faustus, miserable man,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  That from thy soul exclud'st the grace of heaven,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And fly'st the throne of his tribunal-seat!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter DEVILS.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Satan begins to sift me with his pride:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  As in this furnace God shall try my faith,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  My faith, vile hell, shall triumph over thee.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Ambitious fiends, see how the heavens smile\n<br>Â Â Â Â  At your repulse, and laugh your state to scorn!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Hence, hell! for hence I fly unto my God.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exeunt,âon one side, DEVILS, on the other, OLD MAN.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter FAUSTUS,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000380\">167</$link> with SCHOLARS.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Ah, gentlemen!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FIRST SCHOLAR. What ails Faustus?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Ah, my sweet chamber-fellow, had I lived with thee,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  then had I lived still! but now I die eternally.Â  Look, comes\n<br>Â Â Â Â  he not? comes he not?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  SECOND SCHOLAR. What means Faustus?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  THIRD SCHOLAR. Belike he is grown into some sickness by being\n<br>Â Â Â Â  over-solitary.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FIRST SCHOLAR. If it be so, we'll have physicians to cure him.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  â'Tis but a surfeit; never fear, man.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. A surfeit of deadly sin, that hath damned both body\n<br>Â Â Â Â  and soul.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  SECOND SCHOLAR. Yet, Faustus, look up to heaven; remember God's\n<br>Â Â Â Â  mercies are infinite.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. But Faustus' offence can ne'er be pardoned:Â  the serpent\n<br>Â Â Â Â  that tempted Eve may be saved, but not Faustus.Â  Ah, gentlemen,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  hear me with patience, and tremble not at my speeches!Â  Though\n<br>Â Â Â Â  my heart pants and quivers to remember that I have been a student\n<br>Â Â Â Â  here these thirty years, O, would I had never seen Wertenberg,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  never read book! and what wonders I have done, all Germany can\n<br>Â Â Â Â  witness, yea, all the world; for which Faustus hath lost both\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Germany and the world, yea, heaven itself, heaven, the seat of\n<br>Â Â Â Â  God, the throne of the blessed, the kingdom of joy; and must\n<br>Â Â Â Â  remain in hell for ever, hell, ah, hell, for ever!Â  Sweet friends,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  what shall become of Faustus, being in hell for ever?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  THIRD SCHOLAR. Yet, Faustus, call on God.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. On God, whom Faustus hath abjured! on God, whom Faustus\n<br>Â Â Â Â  hath blasphemed!Â  Ah, my God, I would weep! but the devil draws in\n<br>Â Â Â Â  my tears.Â  Gush forth blood, instead of tears! yea, life and soul!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  O, he stays my tongue!Â  I would lift up my hands; but see, they\n<br>Â Â Â Â  hold them, they hold them!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  ALL. Who, Faustus?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Lucifer and Mephistophilis.Â  Ah, gentlemen, I gave them\n<br>Â Â Â Â  my soul for my cunning!<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000382\">168</$link>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  ALL. God forbid!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. God forbade it, indeed; but Faustus hath done it:Â  for\n<br>Â Â Â Â  vain pleasure of twenty-four years hath Faustus lost eternal joy\n<br>Â Â Â Â  and felicity.Â  I writ them a bill with mine own blood:Â  the date\n<br>Â Â Â Â  is expired; the time will come, and he will fetch me.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FIRST SCHOLAR. Why did not Faustus tell us of this before,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000384\">169</$link>Â Â Â Â  that divines might have prayed for thee?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Oft have I thought to have done so; but the devil\n<br>Â Â Â Â  threatened to tear me in pieces, if I named God, to fetch both\n<br>Â Â Â Â  body and soul, if I once gave ear to divinity:Â  and now 'tis too\n<br>Â Â Â Â  late.Â  Gentlemen, away, lest you perish with me.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  SECOND SCHOLAR. O, what shall we do to save<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000386\">170</$link> Faustus?\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Talk not of me, but save yourselves, and depart.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  THIRD SCHOLAR. God will strengthen me; I will stay with Faustus.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FIRST SCHOLAR. Tempt not God, sweet friend; but let us into the\n<br>Â Â Â Â  next room, and there pray for him.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Ay, pray for me, pray for me; and what noise soever\n<br>Â Â Â Â  ye hear,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000388\">171</$link> come not unto me, for nothing can rescue me.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  SECOND SCHOLAR. Pray thou, and we will pray that God may have\n<br>Â Â Â Â  mercy upon thee.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Gentlemen, farewell:Â  if I live till morning, I'll visit\n<br>Â Â Â Â  you; if not, Faustus is gone to hell.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  ALL. Faustus, farewell.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exeunt SCHOLARS.âThe clock strikes eleven.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  FAUSTUS. Ah, Faustus,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Now hast thou but one bare hour to live,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And then thou must be damn'd perpetually!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Stand still, you ever-moving spheres of heaven,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  That time may cease, and midnight never come;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Fair Nature's eye, rise, rise again, and make\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Perpetual day; or let this hour be but\n<br>Â Â Â Â  A year, a month, a week, a natural day,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  That Faustus may repent and save his soul!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  O lente,<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000390\">172</$link> lente currite, noctis equi!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  The stars move still, time runs, the clock will strike,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  The devil will come, and Faustus must be damn'd.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  O, I'll leap up to my God!âWho pulls me down?â\n<br>Â Â Â Â  See, see, where Christ's blood streams in the firmament!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  One drop would save my soul, half a drop:Â  ah, my Christ!â\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Ah, rend not my heart for naming of my Christ!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Yet will I call on him:Â  O, spare me, Lucifer!â\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Where is it now? 'tis gone:Â  and see, where God\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Stretcheth out his arm, and bends his ireful brows!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Mountains and hills, come, come, and fall on me,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And hide me from the heavy wrath of God!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  No, no!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Then will I headlong run into the earth:\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Earth, gape!Â  O, no, it will not harbour me!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  You stars that reign'd at my nativity,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Whose influence hath allotted death and hell,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Now draw up Faustus, like a foggy mist.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Into the entrails of yon labouring cloud[s],\n<br>Â Â Â Â  That, when you<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000392\">173</$link> vomit forth into the air,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  My limbs may issue from your smoky mouths,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  So that my soul may but ascend to heaven!\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [The clock strikes the half-hour.]\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Ah, half the hour is past! 'twill all be past anon\n<br>Â Â Â Â  O God,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  If thou wilt not have mercy on my soul,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Yet for Christ's sake, whose blood hath ransom'd me,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Impose some end to my incessant pain;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Let Faustus live in hell a thousand years,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  A hundred thousand, and at last be sav'd!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  O, no end is limited to damned souls!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Why wert thou not a creature wanting soul?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Or why is this immortal that thou hast?\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Ah, Pythagoras' metempsychosis, were that true,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  This soul should fly from me, and I be chang'd\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Unto some brutish beast!<$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000395\">174</$link> all beasts are happy,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  For, when they die,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Their souls are soon dissolv'd in elements;\n<br>Â Â Â Â  But mine must live still to be plagu'd in hell.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Curs'd be the parents that engender'd me!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  No, Faustus, curse thyself, curse Lucifer\n<br>Â Â Â Â  That hath depriv'd thee of the joys of heaven.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [The clock strikes twelve.]\n<br>Â Â Â Â  O, it strikes, it strikes!Â  Now, body, turn to air,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Or Lucifer will bear thee quick to hell!\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Thunder and lightning.]\n<br>Â Â Â Â  O soul, be chang'd into little water-drops,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And fall into the ocean, ne'er be found!\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter DEVILS.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  My God, my god, look not so fierce on me!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Adders and serpents, let me breathe a while!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Ugly hell, gape not! come not, Lucifer!\n<br>Â Â Â Â  I'll burn my books!âAh, Mephistophilis!\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exeunt DEVILS with FAUSTUS.]Â  <$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/65fb807d23063af6/text/000000397\">175</$link>\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Enter CHORUS.\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  CHORUS. Cut is the branch that might have grown full straight,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  And burned is Apollo's laurel-bough,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  That sometime grew within this learned man.\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Faustus is gone:Â  regard his hellish fall,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Whose fiendful fortune may exhort the wise,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Only to wonder at unlawful things,\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Whose deepness doth entice such forward wits\n<br>Â Â Â Â  To practice more than heavenly power permits.\n<br>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [Exit.]\n<br>\n<br>Â Â Â Â  Terminat hora diem; terminat auctor opus.\n<br></div></div>"
        },
